<h2>The question</h2>
<p>
    <a href="/backlog/1687-webrouting-technical-config-home-schema-in-webrouting-vs-a-p/">#1687</a> (under the
    <a href="/backlog/1684-scaffold-the-webrouting-standard-route-format-profile-url-as/">webrouting</a> scaffold epic)
    asks where the <strong>technical routing knobs</strong> the
    <a href="/intents/navigation/">Navigation Intent</a> deliberately excludes as non-UX — base path, history mode
    (browser / hash / memory), lazy / code-split, prerender, scroll-restoration policy, 404 fallback — are declared as a
    <strong>contract</strong>, and whether a <strong>plateau Technical Configurator domain</strong> assists choosing
    values. Three candidate homes: <strong>(a)</strong> a route-config schema owned by webrouting in WE;
    <strong>(b)</strong> a Technical Configurator domain in plateau-app over those knobs; <strong>(c)</strong> both.
</p>

<h2>Why these knobs can't live in the Navigation Intent</h2>
<p>
    The platform rule <em>intents are UX-only; technical strategy &rarr; Configurator</em>
    (<code>docs/agent/platform-decisions.md#intents-ux-only</code>) is explicit: an intent carries no implementation
    refs. The Navigation Intent (<code>src/_data/intents/navigation.json</code>) owns the
    user-perceivable axes (<code>structure / history / scroll / transition / guard / persistence</code>) — note its
    <code>history</code> is the UX <em>contribution</em> (push / replace / none, "what Back does"), <em>not</em> the
    technical <em>history mode</em> (browser / hash / memory, "how the URL is encoded"). The technical mode is a
    different axis. So these knobs are correctly excluded from the intent and need another home.
</p>

<h2>The standing test collapses (a)-vs-(b) to support-both</h2>
<p>
    Under <em>constellation-placement</em>, <em>bias-toward-separation</em> and <em>config-extends-platform-default</em>,
    "schema vs Configurator" is not a real either/or. Code that <strong>defines a contract</strong> &rarr; WE; a
    <strong>developer-operated tool that walks you through choices against your own build</strong> &rarr; plateau
    (the <em>devtools-placement</em> consumer test). So the <em>schema</em> is the contract source-of-truth in WE and a
    <em>Configurator domain</em> is downstream tooling over it. That is option (c) with WE-as-SoT — and the two coexist,
    so they are not a decision. The genuine residual fork is <strong>which knobs</strong> the unified schema actually
    adds.
</p>

<h2>WE already owns scattered route-config vocabulary</h2>
<p>
    The <a href="/blocks/router/">router</a> block (<code>src/_data/blocks/router.json</code>) <strong>already</strong>
    declares technical-config knobs as attributes / properties on <code>&lt;we-route-view&gt;</code> and child
    <code>&lt;template&gt;</code>: <code>base</code> (base path prepended to all patterns), <code>scroll</code>
    (restoration mode), <code>transition</code> (View Transitions), <code>keep-alive</code> (cache deactivated content),
    and <code>lazy</code> (lazy-load on first navigation). So WE is not greenfield here — it owns the vocabulary, just
    <em>scattered as per-element block attributes</em>, not a unified named schema. The <strong>net-new</strong> knobs a
    config schema adds over what the block already declares are <strong>history mode</strong> (browser / hash / memory),
    <strong>prerender</strong>, and <strong>404 fallback</strong>.
</p>

