<p>
    The split is consistent: <strong>base path, prerender, trailing-slash and 404 fallback are declared CONFIG</strong>
    in the file-system frameworks (Next / SvelteKit) — they are deploy-shaped facts the bundler / host reads without a
    running app. <strong>History mode, scroll, and lazy/code-split lean CODE</strong> — constructor arguments
    (<code>createWebHistory</code>), render functions (<code>scrollBehavior</code>), or per-route imports. This validates
    that a route-config <em>schema</em> is the right WE home for the deploy-shaped, serializable knobs (history mode,
    prerender, 404 fallback, base), and that the code-shaped ones (scroll fn, lazy import) are author-in-the-markup
    concerns the block already covers.
</p>

<h2>The plateau Configurator precedent &mdash; and its converse-guard</h2>
<p>
    plateau-app already runs a data-driven <strong>Technical Configurator</strong>
    (<code>plateau:src/technical-configurator/</code>) whose domains are exactly the "WE schema + downstream tooling"
    pattern: <code>plateau:src/technical-configurator/seed-render-strategy.ts</code> (over WE's #079 Render Strategy
    Protocol) and <code>plateau:src/technical-configurator/seed-file-upload.ts</code> (over the WE file-update
    transfer-strategy) walk a developer through <strong>outcomes</strong> ("does first paint need no JS?", "where do the
    bytes land?") and emit the strategy. A new domain is one seed file
    (<code>seed-&lt;id&gt;.ts</code>) + one line in <code>plateau:src/technical-configurator/provider.ts</code> — no UI
    change. So a routing Configurator domain is mechanically cheap and precedented.
</p>
<p>
    But the <em>intents-UX-only converse-guard</em> (#499) bounds it: a Configurator domain that merely re-homes axes the
    config already carries is <strong>redundant cross-layer duplication</strong>, not the rule's intent — the #499
    credential-enrollment domain was <em>dissolved</em> for exactly this. So a routing Configurator domain is justified
    only if it adds genuine <strong>outcome-framing</strong> value over the schema's enum values (e.g. "your host has no
    rewrite support &rarr; hash history" reasoning), not if it just lists <code>browser / hash / memory</code> the schema
    already names. That makes it a support-both, build-when-it-earns-its-keep concern with one card per documented
    technical setting, not a thing this decision must ship.
</p>

<h2>Recommendation</h2>
<p>
    <strong>(c) WE owns the route-config schema as the source-of-truth; a plateau Configurator domain is optional
    downstream tooling.</strong> The schema follows <em>config-extends-platform-default</em>: per-dimension storage
    (one key per knob in <code>webeverything.config.*</code>), a default-less core, native-first / most-permissive
    defaults, each knob's value <code>extends</code> a platform flavor. It homes the net-new declarable knobs (history
    mode, prerender, 404 fallback) and gives the already-scattered block attributes (base, scroll, lazy) a unified
    named vocabulary. The plateau Configurator domain stays a separately-prioritized build, gated by the #499
    converse-guard, mirroring the render-strategy / file-upload precedent.
</p>
